library(MASS)
library(broom)
library(corrplot)
library(tidyverse)

Data

This data set comes from the UCI Machine Learning Repository and can be found here. According to the data abstract, this data set consists of red vinho verde wine samples from the north of Portugal. The purpose of this data set is to model wine quality based on physicochemical tests. This data set contains one integer variable and the remaining variables are doubles. There are 1,599 red wine samples and 12 variables describing each sample. There are no missing values in this data set. The dependent variable is wine quality.

wine <- read.csv(file = '../data/Wine/winequality-red.csv', sep = ';')
plot(wine)

wine %>% 
  cor() %>%
  corrplot(type = "upper", order = "hclust")

hist(wine$quality, main = "Wine Quality By Score (3-8)")

Most wines have a score of 5 or 6 for quality.

wine$quality <- ifelse(wine$quality > 6, 1, 0)

Any wines with a score > 6 is considered to be of good quality.

stepAIC(glm(quality ~.,
            data = wine,
            family = binomial(link = 'logit')), 
        trace = FALSE)$anova
## Stepwise Model Path 
## Analysis of Deviance Table

## Final Model:
## quality ~ fixed.acidity + volatile.acidity + residual.sugar +

## 4 - free.sulfur.dioxide  1 0.74302331      1590   872.0760 890.0760

The step AIC model selection algorithm suggests that the best model for predicting the quality of wine is the model that uses fixed acidity, volatile acidity, residual sugar, chlorides, total sulfur dioxide, density, sulphates, and alcohol to predict the quality of wine.

model <- glm(quality ~
               fixed.acidity +
               volatile.acidity +
               residual.sugar +
               chlorides + 
               total.sulfur.dioxide +
               density +
               sulphates +
               alcohol,
             data = wine,
             family = binomial(link = 'logit'))
summary(model)

All independent variables in this model are statistically significant with p-values of < 0.001 indicating enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis that there is no relationship between the independent variable and the dependent variable. By the distribution of the deviance residuals, the residuals of the model do not appear to be normally distributed but are close.

plot(model, which = 4, id.n = 4)

There are 4 values that have a much larger Cook’s distance than the rest.

augment(model) %>%
  mutate(index = 1:n()) %>%
  top_n(4, .cooksd) %>%
  dplyr::select(index, .resid, .std.resid, .cooksd)
